919912860300
A) What additional data types are introduced for x86 SIMD and why? Zabit B) Assume that a process has 256 distinct instructions and 16 general-purpose registers, each of which needs a unique number. If an instruction has one opcode, one register operand, and two immediate values, what is the number of bits allocated for each immediate value? C)How are each of the addressing modes different from the others? D) Validate if there exists any data hazard with a proper diagram for the following instruction sequence: ADD EAX, EBX MUL EDX, EAX SUB EDX, EBX
15.12.2023 07:25
919912860300
A) For x86 SIMD (Single Instruction, Multiple Data) instructions, additional data types like XMM (128-bit registers) and YMM (256-bit registers) are introduced to enable parallel processing of multiple data elements in a single instruction, improving performance for tasks like multimedia processing. B) If a process has 256 distinct instructions and 16 registers, and each instruction has one opcode, one register operand, and two immediate values, the number of bits allocated for each immediate value would be log2(256) = 8 bits. C) Different addressing modes in computer architecture include immediate, register, direct, indirect, indexed, and base-plus-index addressing. They differ in how operands are specified or calculated, providing flexibility for addressing data in memory or registers. D) There is a data hazard in the given instruction sequence. The `MUL EDX, EAX` instruction depends on the result of the previous `ADD EAX, EBX` instruction, causing a data hazard. Here's a simple diagram: ``` 1. ADD EAX, EBX | 2. MUL EDX, EAX | 3. SUB EDX, EBX ``` The `MUL` instruction depends on the result of the `ADD` instruction, and the `SUB` instruction depends on the result of the `MUL` instruction, creating a data dependency chain.
15.12.2023 07:25
919912860300
1.A) Design a possible Instruction cycle that supports Interrupts. Present a diagram and mention the purposes of all the stages in your design. B) How is nested interrupts processing better than sequential processing? C)What are the differences in the interconnection designs of Memory and I/O? D) How does PCle improve upon PCI?
15.12.2023 07:25
919912860300
A) Instruction Cycle with Interrupts: 1. **Fetch:** - Purpose: Fetch the next instruction from memory. 2. **Decode:** - Purpose: Decode the fetched instruction to determine the operation to be performed. 3. **Execute:** - Purpose: Execute the decoded instruction. 4. **Interrupt Check:** - Purpose: Check for interrupt requests. 5. **Interrupt Acknowledge:** - Purpose: If an interrupt is pending, acknowledge it and prepare for interrupt handling. 6. **Interrupt Handler:** - Purpose: Execute the interrupt service routine (ISR) for the acknowledged interrupt. 7. **Resume Execution:** - Purpose: Return to the interrupted program and continue the execution. ![Interrupts Design](https://i.imgur.com/X9Rz5nV.png) B) Nested Interrupts vs. Sequential Processing: - **Nested Interrupts:** - Allows handling of higher priority interrupts even when a lower priority interrupt is being processed. - Increases system responsiveness. - Requires a more complex interrupt controller. - **Sequential Processing:** - Handles interrupts in a sequential manner, one at a time. - Simpler to implement but may lead to increased latency for high-priority tasks. Nested interrupts are advantageous in scenarios where timely response to high-priority events is critical. C) Memory vs. I/O Interconnection Designs: - **Memory:** - Typically utilizes a bus-based interconnection. - Direct connection between CPU and memory. - **I/O:** - Often uses I/O controllers and specialized buses. - Indirect connection with the CPU through I/O controllers. Memory has a more direct and straightforward connection with the CPU, while I/O devices often involve additional controller components. D) PCIe vs. PCI: - **PCI (Peripheral Component Interconnect):** - Parallel data bus. - Limited bandwidth. - Shared bus architecture, leading to potential contention. - **PCI Express (PCIe):** - Serial point-to-point connections. - Higher bandwidth. - Improved scalability with multiple lanes. PCIe improves upon PCI by offering higher data transfer rates, scalability, and a more efficient point-to-point serial connection, reducing contention issues associated with shared buses.
15.12.2023 07:25
919912860300
A) What is the purpose of the Tag field in caching? B) Consider a machine that employs a Direct Mapped cache. It has a total byte-addressable memory of216 bytes in which, each block is of the size of 64 bytes. If the number of lines in the cache is 16, then how is this 16-bit address divided into <tags, line, word>? C) Let us assume that a cache can hold 4 elements at a time. Simulate the cache replacement step-by- step for (i) FIFO (ii) LRU (iii) LFU for the following sequence of requests: [6] <1312561271312454>
15.12.2023 07:25
919912860300
A) The Tag field in caching is used to identify the specific block of data stored in the cache. It helps determine if the requested data is present in the cache or if a cache miss occurs, prompting data retrieval from the main memory. B) In a Direct Mapped cache with 16 lines, each block being 64 bytes, and a total memory size of 216 bytes, you can break down the 16-bit address into <tag, line, word> as follows: - Tag: 7 bits (since 2^7 = 128, and 128 * 64 = 8192 bytes, covering the entire memory) - Line: 4 bits (for 16 lines) - Word: 6 bits (for 64 bytes per block) C) For the cache replacement simulation: (i) FIFO (First In, First Out): - 1: Cache [1312], Miss - 3: Cache [1312, 5612], Miss - 5: Cache [1312, 5612, 612], Miss - 6: Cache [1312, 5612, 612, 712], Miss (ii) LRU (Least Recently Used): - 1: Cache [1312], Miss - 3: Cache [1312, 5612], Miss - 5: Cache [1312, 612, 5612], Miss - 6: Cache [1312, 712, 612, 5612], Miss (iii) LFU (Least Frequently Used): - 1: Cache [1312], Miss - 3: Cache [1312, 5612], Miss - 5: Cache [1312, 5612, 612], Miss - 4: Cache [1312, 5612, 612, 2454], Miss
15.12.2023 07:25
919912860300
3. A) What are the fundamental design issues for any instruction set design? B) What are the little-endian and big-endian formats? How does ARM architecture support both? C) How can nested procedure calls be supported through stacks? Explain with proper diagrams. D) What is Packed data? What is the advantage and disadvantage of the same?
15.12.2023 07:26
919912860300
A) Fundamental design issues for instruction set design include: 1. **Operand Storage**: How operands are specified. 2. **Operand Addressing**: Addressing modes for effective operand retrieval. 3. **Instruction Format**: The arrangement of fields in an instruction word. 4. **Instruction Types**: The range and variety of instructions supported. 5. **Data Types**: The representation and manipulation of data types. 6. **Registers**: The number and types of registers used. B) Little-endian and big-endian are byte-order formats. In little-endian, the least significant byte is stored first, while in big-endian, the most significant byte is stored first. ARM supports both through modes that can be configured based on system requirements. C) Nested procedure calls are supported through stacks by saving the return address and local variables of each procedure on the stack. The stack pointer keeps track of the top of the stack. Diagrammatically, it looks like this: ``` +-----------------------+ | Return Address 1 | <-- Top of Stack +-----------------------+ | Local Variables 1 | +-----------------------+ | Return Address 2 | +-----------------------+ | Local Variables 2 | +-----------------------+ | ... | +-----------------------+ ``` D) Packed data refers to storing multiple data elements in a single data structure. The advantage is efficient use of memory, but the disadvantage is potential complexity in accessing individual elements. For example, SIMD (Single Instruction, Multiple Data) instructions operate on packed data, providing parallel processing for multiple data elements simultaneously.

"Dancing with Systems" by Donella Meadows is a powerful essay that explores the dynamics of systems thinking. Here are five key points: Interconnectedness: Meadows emphasizes the interconnected nature of systems, where elements are interdependent and influence each other. Understanding these relationships is crucial for effective system analysis. Leverage Points: The essay introduces the concept of leverage points‚Äîplaces within a system where small changes can lead to significant shifts. Identifying and targeting these points allows for more impactful interventions. Resilience and Stability: Meadows discusses the balance between resilience and stability within a system. Too much stability can lead to stagnation, while too little can result in chaos. Recognizing this delicate balance is essential for managing complex systems. Unintended Consequences: The essay highlights the importance of anticipating and mitigating unintended consequences that may arise from interventions in a system. Actions within a system can have ripple effects, and understanding these repercussions is crucial. Mental Models: Meadows emphasizes the role of mental models in shaping our perceptions of systems. Challenging and refining these mental models allows for a deeper understanding of complex systems, fostering better decision-making and problem-solving. Message ChatGPT‚Ä¶ ChatGPT can make mistakes. CREATE TABLE EMP ( ID NUMBER, SAL NUMBER, AGE NUMBER ); INSERT INTO EMP VALUES (22, 2000, 30); DECLARE E_ID NUMBER; E_SAL NUMBER; E_AGE NUMBER; CURSOR E_CUR IS SELECT * FROM EMP WHERE AGE > 20; BEGIN OPEN E_CUR; LOOP FETCH E_CUR INTO E_ID, E_SAL, E_AGE; EXIT WHEN E_CUR%NOTFOUND; DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('ID: ' || E_ID || ', SAL: ' || E_SAL || ', AGE: ' || E_AGE); END LOOP; CLOSE E_CUR; END; /

def uncommon_characters(str1, str2): uncommon_chars = set(str1) ^ set(str2) result = ''.join(char for char in str1 + str2 if char in uncommon_chars) return result string1 = input("Enter the first string: ") string2 = input("Enter the second string: ") output = uncommon_characters(string1, string2) print("Output:", output)

total_population = 80000 percentage_men = 52 percentage_literacy = 48 percentage_literate_men = 35 # Calculate the number of men and women in the population men = (percentage_men / 100) * total_population women = total_population - men # Calculate the number of literate men literate_men = (percentage_literate_men / 100) * total_population # Calculate the number of illiterate men illiterate_men = men - literate_men # Calculate the number of illiterate women illiterate_women = women - (percentage_literacy / 100) * women print(f"Total number of illiterate men: {int(illiterate_men)}") print(f"Total number of illiterate women: {int(illiterate_women)}")

def is_divisible_by_5(binary_number): decimal_number = int(binary_number, 2) return decimal_number % 5 == 0 def main(): input_sequence = input("Enter a sequence of comma-separated 4-digit binary numbers: ") binary_numbers = input_sequence.split(',') divisible_by_5 = [binary for binary in binary_numbers if is_divisible_by_5(binary.strip())] print(f"Numbers divisible by 5: {', '.join(divisible_by_5)}") if __name__ == "__main__": main()

def calculate_notes(amount): denominations = [100, 50, 10, 5, 2, 1] notes_count = {} for denomination in denominations: if amount >= denomination: notes_count[denomination] = amount // denomination amount %= denomination else: notes_count[denomination] = 0 return notes_count # Input withdrawal_amount = int(input("Enter the amount to be withdrawn: ")) # Calculate and print the result notes_result = calculate_notes(withdrawal_amount) print("Currency notes breakdown:") for denomination, count in notes_result.items(): print(f"{denomination} denomination notes: {count}")

def count_days_occurrences(input_string): days = ("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun") occurrences = {day: 0 for day in days} for i in range(0, len(input_string), 3): day = input_string[i:i+3] if day in days: occurrences[day] += 1 for day, count in occurrences.items(): print(f"{day}-{count}") # Input input_days_string = input("Enter the string of days without separators: ") # Calculate and print the result count_days_occurrences(input_days_string)

def find_even_digit_numbers(start, end): even_digit_numbers = [] for number in range(start, end + 1): digits = [int(digit) for digit in str(number)] if all(digit % 2 == 0 for digit in digits): even_digit_numbers.append(str(number)) return even_digit_numbers # Input start_range = int(input("Enter the starting range: ")) end_range = int(input("Enter the ending range: ")) # Ensure valid range if 1000 <= start_range <= end_range <= 3000: result = find_even_digit_numbers(start_range, end_range) print(",".join(result)) else: print("Invalid input range. Ensure 1000 <= start <= end <= 3000.")

write a program to find the average and sum value of the numbers in a given tuple of n tuples note: read the input as line and parse it into tuple of n tuples based on parenthesis input:((10,10,10,12),(30,45,56,45),(81,80,39,32),(1,2,3,4)
19.01.2024 15:23
919392985417
def calculate_average_sum(tuple_of_tuples): num_tuples = len(tuple_of_tuples) num_elements = len(tuple_of_tuples[0]) # Initialize sums for each position sum_values = [0] * num_elements # Calculate sum for each position for tup in tuple_of_tuples: for i in range(num_elements): sum_values[i] += tup[i] # Calculate average for each position average_values = [sum_val / num_tuples for sum_val in sum_values] return average_values, sum_values def main(): input_str = input("Enter the tuple of tuples as a single line: ") input_str = input_str.strip() # Parse input into a tuple of n tuples try: tuple_of_tuples = eval(input_str) except SyntaxError: print("Invalid input format. Please use proper tuple notation.") return # Check if the input is a tuple of tuples if not isinstance(tuple_of_tuples, tuple) or any(not isinstance(tup, tuple) for tup in tuple_of_tuples): print("Invalid input format. Please provide a tuple of tuples.") return average_values, sum_values = calculate_average_sum(tuple_of_tuples) print(f"Sum values: {sum_values}") print(f"Average values: {average_values}") if __name__ == "__main__": main()

```python # Accepting the sequence of comma separated binary numbers binary_nums = input("Enter the sequence of comma separated 4-digit binary numbers: ") # Splitting the input into individual numbers nums = binary_nums.split(",") # Initializing an empty list to store the divisible numbers divisible_nums = [] # Checking each number if it is divisible by 5 for num in nums: # Converting binary to decimal decimal_num = int(num, 2) # Checking if the decimal number is divisible by 5 if decimal_num % 5 == 0: divisible_nums.append(num) # Joining the divisible numbers into a comma separated sequence result = ",".join(divisible_nums) # Printing the result print("Numbers divisible by 5: " + result) ```

define a function to implement binary search on a given list functions takes two parameters search_key and search_list as given below your program should read a list of values and a key from input and print the index of key if found otherwise -1 note sort the list in increasing order before passing it to binary search

def binary_search(search_list, search_key): # Sort the list in increasing order search_list.sort() low = 0 high = len(search_list) - 1 index = -1 while low <= high: mid = (low + high) // 2 if search_list[mid] == search_key: index = mid break elif search_list[mid] < search_key: low = mid + 1 else: high = mid - 1 return index def main(): input_list = input("Enter a list of values separated by spaces: ") search_key = input("Enter the key to search: ") # Convert input string to a list of integers try: values = [int(val) for val in input_list.split()] except ValueError: print("Invalid input. Please enter a list of integers.") return result = binary_search(values, int(search_key)) if result != -1: print(f"Key {search_key} found at index {result}.") else: print(f"Key {search_key} not found in the list.") if __name__ == "__main__": main()

def process_words(input_str): words = input_str.split() unique_words = sorted(set(words), key=str.lower) result = ' '.join(unique_words) return result def main(): input_sequence = input("Enter a sequence of whitespace-separated words: ") processed_result = process_words(input_sequence) print("Output:", processed_result) if __name__ == "__main__": main()

def binary_search(search_list, search_key): # Make a copy of the list to preserve the original order sorted_list = sorted(search_list) low = 0 high = len(sorted_list) - 1 index = -1 while low <= high: mid = (low + high) // 2 if sorted_list[mid] == search_key: index = mid break elif sorted_list[mid] < search_key: low = mid + 1 else: high = mid - 1 return index # Rest of the code remains unchanged

Dear All, The Indian Air Force is conducting an interaction drive on 15 Dec 2023 in our campus. DISHA has developed an lnduction Publicity Exhibition Vehicle (IPEV), which is a mobile platform accommodating various facets pertaining to IAF so that the target youth get to experience the feel of IAF at their door step through the various appealing zones/equipment that are available in the IPEV. The IPEV has a Reception Zone which contains self-interactive Touch Screen lnformation Kiosks for accessing career information. Flying simulator zone which gives Virtual experience of various operations of IAF through the VR headsets and Flying clothing zone which contains miniature rnodels of various aircraft that are in the inventory of IAF including Fighter planes, Transport aircraft and Helicopters. There will be one motivational lecture followed by Q &A session between 0930 to 1030 hrs in the auditorium. The exposure to IPEV would be carried out near the academic building, in two batches, from 1030 to 1300 hrs and from 1400 to 1600 hrs. The programme would be accompanied by 03 Officers, 08 Airmen, and 02 NC (E). All are requested to kindly join the event. Regards AD, Training and Placements

def perform_operations(input_string, word1, word2, word3): if word1 in input_string and word2 in input_string and word3 in input_string: if input_string.index(word1) < input_string.index(word2): result_string = input_string.replace(word2, word3) else: result_string = input_string.replace(word1, word3) else: result_string = input_string.replace(word1, "TEMP").replace(word2, word1).replace("TEMP", word2) return result_string if __name__ == "__main__": user_string = input("Enter a string: ") user_word1 = input("Enter word1: ") user_word2 = input("Enter word2: ") user_word3 = input("Enter word3: ") result = perform_operations(user_string, user_word1, user_word2, user_word3) print("Result: ", result)

SystemVerilog Code: module FullAdder ( input logic A, B, Cin, output logic Sum, Cout ); // Sum bit calculation assign Sum = A ^ B ^ Cin; // Cout calculation assign Cout = (A & B) | (B & Cin) | (A & Cin); endmodule SystemC Code: #include <systemc.h> SC_MODULE(FullAdder) { sc_in<bool> A, B, Cin; sc_out<bool> Sum, Cout; // Constructor SC_CTOR(FullAdder) { SC_METHOD(addition_process); sensitive << A << B << Cin; } // Full adder logic void addition_process() { Sum.write(A.read() ^ B.read() ^ Cin.read()); Cout.write((A.read() & B.read()) | (B.read() & Cin.read()) | (A.read() & Cin.read())); } }; int sc_main(int argc, char* argv[]) { // Signals sc_signal<bool> A, B, Cin, Sum, Cout; // Instantiate FullAdder module FullAdder full_adder("FullAdder"); full_adder.A(A); full_adder.B(B); full_adder.Cin(Cin); full_adder.Sum(Sum); full_adder.Cout(Cout); // Initialize inputs A = 1; B = 0; Cin = 1; // Run the simulation sc_start(1, SC_NS); // Display results cout << "Sum: " << Sum.read() << endl; cout << "Cout: " << Cout.read() << endl; return 0; }

Sure, here are three different ways to create an API using Go and three different libraries for handling HTTP requests: 1. Using the `net/http` package: ``` package main import ( "fmt" "net/http" ) func main() { http.HandleFunc("/", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) { http.Redirect(w, r, "/docs", http.StatusTemporaryRedirect) }) http.HandleFunc("/docs", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) { fmt.Fprint(w, "Under construction!") }) http.ListenAndServe(":8080", nil) } ``` This code sets up an HTTP server on port 8080 and defines two handlers: one for the root URL ("/") and another for the "/docs" URL. The handler for the root URL redirects any incoming requests to the "/docs" URL using the `http.Redirect` function. The handler for the "/docs" URL simply writes the string "Under construction!" to the response writer. 2. Using the `github.com/gorilla/mux` package: ``` package main import ( "fmt" "log" "net/http" "github.com/gorilla/mux" ) func main() { r := mux.NewRouter() r.Get("/", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) { http.Redirect(w, r, "/docs", http.StatusTemporaryRedirect) }) r.Get("/docs", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) { fmt.Fprint(w, "Under construction!") }) log.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(":8080", r)) } ``` This code uses the `github.com/gorilla/mux` package to define a router that maps URLs to handlers. It defines two handlers: one for the root URL ("/") and another for the "/docs" URL. The handler for the root URL redirects any incoming requests to the "/docs" URL using the `http.Redirect` function. The handler for the "/docs" URL simply writes the string "Under construction!" to the response writer. 3. Using the `google.golang.org/grpc/grpc-gateway/runtime` package: ``` package main import ( "context" "fmt" "log" "net/http" "google.golang.org/grpc/grpc-gateway/runtime" ) type underConstruction struct{} func (u *underConstruction) ServeHTTP(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) { fmt.Fprint(w, "Under construction!") } func main() { ctx := context.Background() mux := runtime.NewServerMetadataMux(nil) opts := []runtime.ServerOption{ runtime.WithMarshalerOption(runtime.MIMEUnmarshal), runtime.WithServerStreamInterceptor(grpc.ChainUnaryInterceptor( func(ctx context.Context, req interface{}, info *grpc.UnaryServerInfo, handler grpc.UnaryHandler) (interface{}, error) { return &underConstruction{}, nil }, )), } srv := runtime.NewServer(ctx, mux, opts...) log.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(":8080", srv)) } ``` This code defines a gRPC server using the `google.golang.org/grpc/grpc-gateway/runtime` package. It defines a single service, `underConstruction`, which has a single method, `ServeHTTP`, that writes the string "Under construction!" to the response writer. The server is started on port 8080 using the `http.ListenAndServe` function.

import cmath def DTb(num): if num >= 1: DTb(num // 2) print(num % 2, end = '') def dto(num): if num >= 1: dto(num // 8) print(num % 8, end = '') def dth(num): if num >= 1: dth(num // 16) y=num%16 if y<= 9: print(y, end = '') elif y==10: print("A",end='') elif y==11: print("B",end='') elif y==12: print("C",end='') elif y==13: print("D",end='') elif y==14: print("D",end='') elif y==15: print("E",end='') x= int(input("enter a number")) DTb(x) print("\n") dto(x) print("\n") dth(x)

IIIT Kota Central Library was inaugurated on October 2, 2023. The Central Library is located at 2nd floor of the Academic¬†block. For smooth functioning of the library and coordination with all faculty members, students and staff, Library Committee and Library Advisory Committee for IIIT Kota have been constituted. IIIT Kota Central Library provides book bank facility to IIIT Kota undergraduate students which was started in July 2018. Per day circulation of books and number of visitors in library is around 41 and 113 respectively. Total numbers of books in IIIT Kota library are 6770 (as on 30.10.2023). Additionally, 7 vendors were empanelled in the session 2019-20 and the books were purchased through Vendors in this year.
06.11.2023 22:06
917891541995
Library content
06.11.2023 22:06
917891541995
The canteen at IIIT Kota plays a crucial role in the daily life of students. The building was inaugurated on the 2nd of October 2023, by the honorable Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi. Its strategic placement adjacent to the mess building not only enhances convenience but also fosters a warm and inclusive environment that encourages students to socialize. Operated by Vinay Enterprises, the canteen stands out for its unwavering dedication to ensuring the availability of nourishing and hygienic food options, a commitment highly prioritized by the institution's governing body. A noteworthy feature of the canteen is its extended work hours, operational from 10 am to 2 am. This extended schedule caters to students' late-night study sessions and project work, ensuring that no one goes hungry during these crucial periods. In essence, the IIIT Kota canteen offers nourishing food, a comfortable environment, and the flexibility to accommodate the diverse schedules of its students.

917891541995
The Computer Centre at IIIT Kota, inaugurated on the 2nd of October 2023 by Prime Minister Shri Narendra Modi, is a technological hub at the heart of the campus. It offers a total of 90 computer workstations, each designed to meet high-performance computing needs. These computers come equipped with reliable and robust specifications, including 4GB of RAM and a spacious 500GB hard drive (HDD). They are powered by advanced processors, either Core i5 or Core i7, which are known for their processing speed and efficiency. These machines are optimized for demanding computational tasks, making them ideal for students and researchers working on a wide range of projects. The Computer Centre reflects IIIT Kota's commitment to providing top-tier resources to students and faculty. This cutting-edge facility is a vital component of the institution's technological infrastructure, supporting various research, development, and academic activities in the field of computer science and technology.

917891541995
The canteen at IIIT Kota plays a crucial role in the daily life of students. The building was inaugrated on the 2nd of October 2023, by none other than honerable Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi. Its strategic placement adjacent to the mess building not only enhances convenience but also fosters a warm and inclusive environment that encourages students to socialize. Operated by Vinay Enterprises, the canteen stands out for its unwavering dedication to ensuring the availability of nourishing and hygienic food options, a commitment highly prioritized by the institution's governing body. A noteworthy feature of the canteen is its extended work hours, operational from 10 am to 2 am. This extended schedule caters to students' late-night study sessions and project work, ensuring that no one goes hungry during these crucial periods. In essence, the IIIT Kota canteen offers nourishing food, a comfortable environment, and the flexibility to accommodate the diverse schedules of its students.

06.11.2023 20:59
917206578853
The Computer Centre at IIIT Kota, inaugurated on the 2nd of October 2023 by Prime Minister Shri Narendra Modi, is a technological hub at the heart of the campus. It offers a total of 90 computer workstations, each designed to meet high-performance computing needs. These computers come equipped with reliable and robust specifications, including 4GB of RAM and a spacious 500GB hard drive (HDD). They are powered by advanced processors, either Core i5 or Core i7, which are known for their processing speed and efficiency. These machines are optimized for demanding computational tasks, making them ideal for students and researchers working on a wide range of projects. The Computer Centre reflects IIIT Kota's commitment to providing top-tier resources to students and faculty. This cutting-edge facility is a vital component of the institution's technological infrastructure, supporting various research, development, and academic activities in the field of computer science and technology.

IIIT Kota Central Library was inaugurated on October 2, 2023. The Central Library is located at 2nd floor of the Academic¬†block. For smooth functioning of the library and coordination with all faculty members, students and staff, Library Committee and Library Advisory Committee for IIIT Kota have been constituted. IIIT Kota Central Library provides book bank facility to IIIT Kota undergraduate students which was started in July 2018. Per day circulation of books and number of visitors in library is around 41 and 113 respectively. Total numbers of books in IIIT Kota library are 6770 (as on 30.10.2023). Additionally, 7 vendors were empanelled in the session 2019-20 and the books were purchased through Vendors in this year. üåê **Open Source Unveiled!** üåê üîç **What's Open Source?** Open source is collaborative, transparent software development. It means free code, collaboration, and user freedom. üë• **Open Source Community** Passionate individuals globally join forces, innovating together. üí° **Contribution Defined** Contributing = actively participating in a project, coding, documentation, design, testing, and support. üöÄ **Why Contribute?** - **Learn & Grow**: Gain real experience, learn, and enhance skills. - **Portfolio Builder**: Showcase work for your career. - **Make an Impact**: Work on projects with real-world effects. - **Community Connection**: Bond with like-minded global collaborators. üåç **Where to Contribute?** - **GitHub**: Search for projects. - **Linux**: The open source OS. - **Mozilla**: Home of Firefox and more. - **WordPress**: Popular for websites. There's a project for everyone, regardless of expertise. Join us, make your mark, and be part of something bigger! Questions about open source? Comment below, and let's guide you! üí™ #OpenSource #Contribution #TechCommunity This condensed version maintains the core information and encourages engagement.
